full_content.content: Common reasons your Whirlpool washer is not draining
The most common reasons your Whirlpool washer is not draining are a broken motor, malfunctioning electronic control board or a jammed door lock assembly.
We can help! Our service technicians have repaired over
Whirlpool washers. We can fix yours no matter where you bought it.
Most common repairs needed to fix a Whirlpool washer

A broken washer motor will prevent the spin basket from rotating or agitating, and can also cause a variety of other issues that affect the washer’s ability to function properly. Signs that the motor is wearing out include unusual noises during operation, such as grinding or squealing sounds. The washer may also exhibit erratic spinning or agitation, with clothes not being properly rinsed or still soaking wet after the spin cycle. Additionally, a worn-out motor may lead to the washer not completing its cycles, stopping abruptly, or not starting at all. Burnt smells or overheating around the motor area can be indicative of internal problems. In some cases, visible damage to the motor itself may be apparent.
How to replace the motor in a washer

A malfunctioning electronic control board can lead to various failures in a washer. This is because the board serves as the brain of the washer, controlling crucial components such as the water valve, drive motor, drain pump, and cycles. If the electronic control board fails, the washer may not power up or display the cycle status. Additionally, it might fail to fill, agitate, spin, or drain. In some cases, a shorted board may emit a burning smell.
How to replace the electronic control board in a washer

When a washer door lock assembly is jammed, you may encounter difficulty in opening or closing the washer door. The door may not latch properly, leading to issues in starting or completing a wash cycle. The washer might display an error code indicating a door lock problem. During operation, the door lock may make unusual clicking sounds or fail to engage, preventing the washer from starting. Additionally, if there is a malfunction, the door lock indicator light may not illuminate as expected. Users might notice water remaining in the drum even after the wash cycle has finished, indicating a potential problem with the door lock assembly preventing proper drainage.
How to replace the door lock assembly on a washer
What to expect when you experience a Whirlpool washer not draining issue
What causes a Whirlpool washing machine not to drain?

A washer that won’t drain is sometimes caused by simple user errors, such as incorrect cycle settings, an unbalanced load, or a lid/door that isn’t fully closed. Check and resolve these issues first if they exist.

Next, check the house drain for the washer. Use a plumbers snake or call a plumber to clear that drain if it’s clogged. Then you can test the washer and see if it drains properly. If it does, you can skip reading the rest of this article.
If a clogged house drain isn’t causing your washer drain system failure, follow these steps to find and fix the problem.
If your machine still won’t drain, you’ll need to remove the water yourself.
You’ll need a shallow pan, towels, and a bucket.
Unplug the washer and move it away from the wall. Find the drain hose at the back of the machine. Place the shallow pan underneath it.

Lower the end of the drain hose into the bucket. Gravity should allow water to flow out. Raise the drain hose back up and empty the shallow pan into the bucket as the pan fills up. Empty the bucket if that container gets full before draining ends.
If the water doesn’t drain, the hose may be clogged, which brings us to the next step.
Step 2: Inspect and Clear the Drain Hose
A blocked drain hose is a common cause of water not draining.
Use a wet/dry shop vacuum to suck the clog out of the drain hose and remove the water from the washer.
Note: You can also use this method to drain the washer from the beginning instead of using the gravity drain procedure described above.
Not everyone has a wet/dry shop vacuum handy.
Here’s how to clear a drain hose clog without using a wet/dry shop vacuum (or if the shop vac wasn’t able to remove the clog):
Disconnect the Drain Hose from the Washer
Use a pair of pliers to release the hose clamp where the hose connects to the washer. Pull the hose free.
Check for Obstructions and Clear the Clog
Shine a flashlight into the hose to check for a clog.
If you don’t find a clog in the drain hose, skip down to the next troubleshooting step.
If the hose is clogged, remove any lint, debris, or small items using one of these methods:
Take the hose outside and run water through the drain hose using a garden hose. This will clear out most washer drain hose clogs.
Use a plumber’s snake or similar item to the clog out of the drain hose.
If you have an air compressor, use compressed air to push the clog out of the drain hose (outdoors of course).
Run water through the drain hose to clear out any residue and ensure it’s completely clear (unless you already used water to clear out the clog).
Once the hose is clean, secure it back onto the washer.
Many front-load washers have a pump filter designed to catch lint, coins, or other debris that might block water flow.
If that drain pump filter gets too full, water won’t drain from the washer and you’ll need to clear debris from that filter.
If you have a top-load washer skip down to the next troubleshooting step below.

full_content.content: The drain pump filter is often behind a small access panel near the bottom front of the machine. Open that access door to find the drain pump filter.

Some filters include a small drain tube. Use it to empty remaining water into a shallow pan as shown in the image above. (This may take a while if the washer tub is still full because the drain hose wasn’t clogged.)
Remove and Clean the Drain Pump Filter
Place towels under the drain pump filter housing to catch water as you remove the filter.
Twist the drain pump filter cap counterclockwise to release the filter and remove it from the housing.
Clear debris out of the filter and wash the filter under running water.
Clear away any debris and lint inside the housing.
If mold or mildew has developed in the filter and housing, don some protective gloves and use a liquid chlorine bleach and water solution to clean the filter and housing.
Screw the filter back in place.
Reinstall the cap on the small drain tube and clip it back in place.
Close the drain pump filter access panel.
If your washer doesn’t have a small access panel for the drain pump filter, you may be able to access the drain pump filter by remove the bottom part of the front washer panel as shown in this video:
If clearing the hose and filter doesn’t resolve the issue, the problem might lie with the drain pump itself.
Inspect the Drain Pump for Damage
Unplug the washer before accessing the drain pump.

To access the drain pump on a front-load washer, you’ll typically need to remove the front panel as shown in this video:
Here’s a video that shows how to access the drain pump on a common top-load washer:
Disconnect the pump and look for visible cracks or broken components. Also, check if the pump’s impeller (the spinning part) is stuck, clogged or broken.
Clean the pump if it’s clogged and replace the pump if you know that it’s broken.
If you’re unsure whether the drain pump is causing the problem, it’s likely time to schedule
service and have a technician take over and fix the washer.
How is the not draining problem fixed?

Correcting most not draining problems usually involves replacing the motor, electronic control board or door lock assembly. However, there are many potential causes, so a thorough diagnosis is key to fixing the problem. An accurate diagnosis is essential to understanding how much the repair will be.
Sears Home Services recommendations for a washer that is not draining

When the washer is not draining it can be for many reasons. To avoid replacing unneeded parts we recommend having a Sears Home Services professional perform diagnostic tests to identify the root cause of the problem. Our technicians are experienced at diagnosing all types of washer failures.
What to look out for with a washer not draining diagnosis

Diagnosing modern appliances without proper knowledge and training can be difficult. Without using proper diagnostic techniques, fixing your washer problem will only be achieved through changing parts on a hunch. Appliances, especially in the last 10 years, have become extremely advanced, and many models have electronic parts that are difficult to test. DIY repairs on the latest appliance models are becoming increasingly difficult.
Troubleshooting Whirlpool Washer Not Draining Issues

When dealing with a Whirlpool washer that doesn't drain, it’s important to identify the underlying cause promptly. Whether it's a Whirlpool Cabrio, Duet, or any other model, understanding why your Whirlpool washer water is not draining can save you time and money. Common reasons include clogged hoses, faulty drain pumps, or issues with the electronic control board. Regular maintenance and timely inspections can help prevent these issues from occurring, ensuring your washer operates smoothly.

If your Whirlpool Duet washer is not draining, it could be due to several issues. One common problem is a clogged drain pump filter, which can trap debris and prevent water from draining. To check this, locate the filter and clean it out thoroughly. Another potential issue is a faulty drain pump. When the pump fails, your Whirlpool Duet washer will not drain, leaving water in the drum at the end of the cycle. Replacing the drain pump may be necessary to resolve this issue.

The electronic control board could be malfunctioning, preventing the washer from entering the drain cycle. If your Whirlpool Duet washer will not drain, inspecting the control board for any signs of damage or malfunction can help diagnose the problem. In some cases, a reset or replacement of the control board may be required. Regular maintenance and timely repairs can prevent these issues from disrupting your laundry routine.

A Whirlpool Cabrio washer not draining or spinning is a common problem that can be attributed to various causes. A blocked drain hose or a clogged pump filter are usual suspects. Ensuring that the drain hose is free from kinks and blockages can help restore proper drainage. If the pump filter is clogged, cleaning it out can solve the issue.

Sometimes, the problem lies with the lid switch assembly. If the lid switch is defective, the washer won't drain. To determine if this is the issue, you can test the switch for continuity. A faulty switch will need to be replaced to get your Whirlpool Cabrio washer draining and spinning again. Regularly checking these components can help you avoid situations where your Whirlpool Cabrio washer won’t drain or spin, ensuring smooth operation.

In cases where the Whirlpool Cabrio will not drain, it is also important to inspect the electronic control board. Malfunctions in the control board can prevent the washer from completing its drain cycle. If this is suspected, seeking professional assistance to repair or replace the control board is advisable.

For a Whirlpool Thin Twin not draining, the issue often lies with the drain pump or the hose. A clogged drain pump can prevent water from being expelled from the washer. Inspect the pump for blockages and clear any debris. Also check the drain hose for any kinks or obstructions that might be hindering water flow. A clear and unobstructed hose is crucial for proper drainage.

Another aspect to consider is the belt that drives the pump. If the belt is worn out or broken, the pump won't operate effectively, leading to drainage issues. Replacing the worn-out belt can often resolve the problem of your Whirlpool Thin Twin not draining. Regular inspections and maintenance can keep your washer running efficiently and prevent these common drainage problems.

When the Whirlpool washer water is not draining, it could also be due to a malfunctioning water level pressure switch. This switch helps regulate the water level within the washer, and if it fails, it might prevent the washer from draining correctly. Checking and replacing the water level pressure switch can solve this issue.

When your Whirlpool Quiet Partner 2 is not draining, the first step is to check the drain pump and filter for any clogs. Debris such as lint, small clothing items, or other objects can block the pump and filter, preventing water from draining. Cleaning these components can often solve the problem. If the pump itself is faulty, it will need to be replaced to restore proper drainage.

The electronic control board is another potential culprit. If it malfunctions, your Whirlpool Quiet Partner 2 won’t drain properly. Inspecting the control board for any signs of damage or wear can help identify the issue. Replacing a malfunctioning control board is a more complex task that might require professional assistance to ensure it’s done correctly. Regular maintenance checks can help avoid these issues and keep your washer in optimal working condition.

For scenarios where the Whirlpool washer doesn't drain, checking the control board and pump for any electrical issues can be crucial. Addressing these problems promptly can help maintain the efficiency and longevity of your washer.
Whirlpool Top Load Washer Not Draining

A Whirlpool top load washer not draining can be caused by a variety of issues, including a clogged drain pump or hose. Inspect the drain hose for any kinks or blockages, and ensure the pump is free from debris. Clearing these can often restore proper drainage. A malfunctioning lid switch can prevent the washer from entering the drain cycle. Testing the lid switch for continuity can determine if it needs replacement.

In some cases, the problem may be due to the electronic control board or a defective water level pressure switch. If the control board fails, the washer won’t progress through its cycles correctly, leading to drainage issues. Similarly, a faulty water level pressure switch can prevent the washer from draining properly. Addressing these components can help resolve the issue of your Whirlpool top load washer not draining. Regular maintenance and timely repairs are key to preventing such problems and ensuring your washer operates efficiently.

When facing a Whirlpool washer water not draining situation, it is essential to inspect all related components thoroughly. Regular maintenance and timely interventions can help keep your washer running smoothly and avoid prolonged downtime.

full_content.content: Why is my Whirlpool washer not draining?
Check for clogged drain hoses or clogged drain pump filter. Inspect the drain pump for damage.
How do I fix a Whirlpool washer that won’t drain?
Clean out any blockages in the drain hose or pump filter. If the drain pump is broken, replace it.
What causes a Whirlpool washer to not drain?
Clogs in the drain hose, filter or pump, or a malfunctioning pump can prevent drainage.
Can a faulty pump stop my Whirlpool washer from draining?
Yes, a faulty pump can block water from draining. Replacing the pump should solve the issue.

full_content.content: How Does a Mixing Valve Work?
Learn how a mixing valve works to control water temperature in a washer.
What is the drum of the washing machine?
The drum is the core part of the washer that holds your laundry and enables the cleaning process through rotation, agitation, and rinsing.
Hard water is water that contains high levels of dissolved minerals, particularly calcium and magnesium. It contrasts with soft water, which has lower concentrations of these minerals.
What is a Washing Machine Pedestal?
A washing machine pedestal is a platform that raises the washer off the ground, providing easier access to the appliances and often includes additional storage space such as drawers.

A washer tub is the interior part of a washing machine where clothes are placed for washing, typically made of stainless steel, plastic, or porcelain-coated metal, designed to hold water and withstand the agitation or spinning during the wash cycle.
Additional possible Whirlpool washer symptoms you may experience
Whirlpool washer making loud banging noise on spin cycle
Whirlpool washer not finishing the cycle
Whirlpool washer rinse cycle not working
Whirlpool washer won't spin or drain
Whirlpool washer cold water not working
Whirlpool washer control lock won't turn off
